The pattern I see

Everything you’ve been building points toward one transition:

Pantheon should become a machine that manufactures leverage.

Not attention.

Not theories.

Not complexity.

Leverage.

That leverage can then be directed into your concrete goals:

* Wild Hawg as a business that generates cash flow.
* A growing library of reusable methods and software.
* A portfolio of demonstrations that establish credibility.
* More time, financial freedom, and opportunities to spend with your family.
* A research framework that continues to improve because it is continuously tested and refined.

If I were prioritizing the next six months, I’d use a simple rule:

Every week, Pantheon must produce one durable asset and one real-world demonstration.

That cadence compounds. Over a year, you’d have dozens of reusable assets and dozens of concrete examples of what the framework can do, making it far easier for others—and for your future self—to evaluate, improve, and build on it.